HEADWORD: disherit
<hw>dis*her"it</hw> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧s*h⟦ecr⟧r"⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Disherited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Disheriting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧sh⟦eacute⟧riter</ets>; pref. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧s-</ets> (L.
<ets>dis-</ets>) + <ets>h⟦eacute⟧riter</ets> to inherit. See
<er>Inherit</er>, and cf. <er>Dusheir</er>, <er>Disinherit</er>.]</ety>
<def>To disinherit; to cut off, or detain, from the possession or
enjoyment of an inheritance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

